</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>E-commerce Website</h1>
        <p>This is a comprehensive e-commerce website built with a traditional Java-based backend and a modern, responsive frontend. The platform allows users to browse products, add items to a cart, and complete a checkout process.</p>

        <hr class="my-6">

        <h2>Features</h2>
        <ul class="no-list">
            <li class="list-item"><strong>Responsive Design:</strong> The website is fully responsive, providing a seamless shopping experience on desktops, tablets, and mobile devices.</li>
            <li class="list-item"><strong>Product Catalog:</strong> Browse a catalog of products with detailed descriptions and images.</li>
            <li class="list-item"><strong>Shopping Cart:</strong> Add, remove, and update items in a persistent shopping cart.</li>
            <li class="list-item"><strong>User Authentication:</strong> Secure user registration and login functionality.</li>
            <li class="list-item"><strong>Checkout Process:</strong> A simple and secure checkout workflow.</li>
            <li class="list-item"><strong>Admin Panel:</strong> (Optional Feature, assuming for a full e-commerce site) An admin interface for managing products, categories, and orders.</li>
        </ul>

        <hr class="my-6">

        <h2>Technology Stack</h2>
        <div class="text-section">
            <h3>Frontend</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>HTML5:</strong> For the core structure of the web pages.</li>
                <li><strong>CSS3:</strong> For styling and visual presentation.</li>
                <li><strong>JavaScript:</strong> For interactive elements and client-side logic.</li>
                <li><strong>Bootstrap:</strong> A powerful framework for building responsive and mobile-first layouts.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="text-section">
            <h3>Backend</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Core Java:</strong> The foundation of the server-side application logic.</li>
                <li><strong>Servlets:</strong> Handles HTTP requests and responses.</li>
                <li><strong>Hibernate:</strong> An Object-Relational Mapping (ORM) framework to manage database interactions.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="text-section">
            <h3>Database</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>MySQL:</strong> A robust relational database management system for storing all application data.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="text-section">
            <h3>Development Environment</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>NetBeans:</strong> The Integrated Development Environment (IDE) used for developing and managing the project.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <hr class="my-6">

        <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
        <p>To get this project up and running on your local machine, you need to have the following software installed:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>JDK (Java Development Kit)</strong>: Version 8 or higher.</li>
            <li><strong>Apache Tomcat Server</strong>: Version 8.5 or higher.</li>
            <li><strong>MySQL Server</strong>: Version 5.7 or higher.</li>
            <li><strong>NetBeans IDE</strong>: Version 8.2 or higher.</li>
        </ul>

        <hr class="my-6">

        <h2>Getting Started</h2>
        <p>Follow these steps to set up the project locally.</p>
        <div class="text-section">
            <h3>1. Clone the Repository</h3>
            <pre><code>git clone [your-repository-url]
cd [your-project-folder]</code></pre>
        </div>
        <div class="text-section">
            <h3>2. Database Setup</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Open MySQL and create a new database:
                    <pre><code>CREATE DATABASE `ecommerce_db`;</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>Locate the `database.sql` file in the project directory. This file contains the schema for all the tables.</li>
                <li>Execute the `database.sql` script in your new `ecommerce_db` database to create the necessary tables.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="text-section">
            <h3>3. Import into NetBeans</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Open NetBeans and go to `File > Open Project`.</li>
                <li>Navigate to the project folder you cloned and select it. NetBeans will automatically detect the project type and open it.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="text-section">
            <h3>4. Configure Database Connection</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>In NetBeans, find the Hibernate configuration file (e.g., `hibernate.cfg.xml`) and update the database credentials to match your local MySQL setup (username, password, and database name).</li>
                <li>Add the MySQL JDBC driver to the project's libraries.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="text-section">
            <h3>5. Deploy the Project</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Right-click the project in NetBeans.</li>
                <li>Select `Run` or `Clean and Build`. NetBeans will build the project and deploy it to the configured Apache Tomcat server.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <hr class="my-6">

        <h2>How to Use</h2>
        <p>Once the project is deployed, you can access it by opening a web browser and navigating to the local server address (e.g., `http://localhost:8080/[your-project-name]`).</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Home Page:</strong> Browse the latest products.</li>
            <li><strong>Login/Register:</strong> Create a new account or log in to manage your cart and place orders.</li>
            <li><strong>Cart:</strong> View and manage the items you plan to purchase.</li>
            <li><strong>Checkout:</strong> Follow the steps to complete your purchase.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
